losophy and psychotherapy or in the philosophy of emotion. The accompanying commentary explains the philosophical concepts discussed in the text and supplies many helpful parallels from Greek sources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEmotionsvEarly works to 1850. 0aHappinessvEarly works to 1800. 0aHappiness. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  amarcus tullius cicero, emotions, classical literature, classics, tusculan disputations, human emotion, grief, philosopher, philosophical, stoic position, reasoning, morality, morals, classification, anger, politics, war, classicists, psychotherapy, happiness, happy, ancient rome, roman philosophy, tusculanae quaestiones, stoicism, emotional disturbances.1 aGraver, Margaret.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226305196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226305196/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles